T1  - Predicting the Performance of Initial Public Offerings: Should Human Resource Management be in the Equation?
AU  - Welbourne, Theresa M.
AU  - Andrews, Alice O.
Y1  - 1996/08/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256716
DO  - 10.5465/256716
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 891
EP  - 919
VL  - 39
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Population ecology is used to explain the role of human resource management (HRM) in enhancing the performance of initial public offering (IPO) companies. We examined the determinants of structural inertia and developed hypotheses on the relationship between HRM and organizational performance. The results indicate that two human resource variables, human resource value and organization-based rewards, predict initial investor reaction and long-term survival. The rewards variable negatively affects initial performance but positively affects survival.
AB  - Population ecology is used to explain the role of human resource management (HRM) in enhancing the performance of initial public offering (IPO) companies. We examined the determinants of structural inertia and developed hypotheses on the relationship between HRM and organizational performance. The results indicate that two human resource variables, human resource value and organization-based rewards, predict initial investor reaction and long-term survival. The rewards variable negatively affects initial performance but positively affects survival.
